{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (later becoming the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating below in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (later becoming the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating below in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Semibankirschina", "text_new": "{{russianterm\n| russian = \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430\n| rusr = Semibankirschina\n| literal meaning = rule of seven bankers\n}}\n\n'''Semibankirschina''' (\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430), or seven bankers, was a group of seven [[Russia]]n [[business oligarch]]s who played an important role in the political and economical life of Russia between 1996 and 2000. In spite of internal conflicts, the group worked together in order to re-elect President [[Boris Yeltsin]] in 1996, and thereafter to successfully manipulate him and his political environment from behind the scenes.\n\nThe seven businessmen were identified by oligarch [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]] in an October 1996 interview, and the term \"semibankirschina\" was then coined by a journalist in November 1996 as a takeoff on the [[Seven Boyars]] (semiboyarschina), who deposed [[Tsar]] [[Vasili IV of Russia|Vasily Shuisky]] in 1610.\n\n==The seven bankers==\nRussian [[Russian oligarch|oligarch]] [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]], in a 29 October 1996 interview in the ''[[Financial Times]]'', named seven Russian bankers and businessmen that he claimed controlled most of the economy and media in Russia<ref name=persistent>{{cite book|last1=Bojicic-Dzelilovic|first1=Vesna|title=Persistent State Weakness in the Global Age|date=2016|publisher=[[Routledge]]|page=104|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JLgoDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA104}}</ref><ref name=clique>{{cite news|title=British Paper Names Banking Clique|url=http://old.themoscowtimes.com/sitemap/free/1996/11/article/british-paper-names-banking-clique/316590.html/|accessdate=29 March 2018|work=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=5 November 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Russia's Path PT312\"/><ref name=piratization>{{cite book|last1=Goldman|first1=Marshall I.|title=The Piratization of Russia: Russian Reform Goes Awry|date=2003|publisher=[[Routledge]]|page=132|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zP9-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA132}}</ref> and had helped bankroll [[Boris Yeltsin]]\u2019s re-election campaign in 1996.<ref name=\"FT alpha\">{{cite news| title=Mikhail Fridman: The Alpha oligarch| first1=Guy| last1=Chazan| first2=John| last2=Thornhill| url =https://www.ft.com/content/b47de3d4-c325-11e4-ac3d-00144feab7de| work=[[Financial Times]]| date=5 March 2015| accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"qui est\">{{cite news|last1=Schmouker|first1=Olivier|title=Qui est Mikhail Fridman?|url=http://www.lesaffaires.com/secteurs-d-activite/general/qui-est-mikhail-fridman-/507444|accessdate=31 March 2018|work=[[Les Affaires]]|date=9 December 2009|language=French}}</ref><ref name=\"Russia's Path PT312\">{{cite book|last1=Kotz|first1=David|last2=Weir|first2=Fred|title=Russia's Path from Gorbachev to Putin: The Demise of the Soviet System and the New Russia|date=2007|publisher=[[Routledge]]|page=218|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=20OUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT312}}</ref><ref name=piratization/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lloyd|first1=John|title=The Autumn Of the Oligarchs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/08/magazine/the-autumn-of-the-oligarchs.html|accessdate=30 March 2018|work=[[New York Times]]|date=8 October 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe word \"Semibankirschina\" was subsequently coined by the Russian journalist Andrey Fadin of the ''Obschaya Gazeta'' newspaper, in a 14 November 1996 article titled \"Semibankirschina as a New Russian Variation of Semiboyarschina\".<ref>[http://kommersant.ru/doc/390624 Semibankirschina as a New Russian Variation of Semiboyarschina] fragment in the [[Kommersant]] newspaper, June 23, 2003 (in Russian)</ref> He wrote that \"they control the access to budget money and basically all investment opportunities inside the country. They own the gigantic information resource of the major TV channels. They form the President's opinion. Those who didn't want to walk along them were either strangled or left the circle.\" Slightly over a year later, Fadin was killed in a car accident.<ref>Sergei Mitrofanov. ''[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/188217 Journalist Andrei Fadin died]''. [[Kommersant]] newspaper, November 22, 1997 (in Russian)</ref> [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]] also used this word in his critical 1998 essay ''Russia under Avalanche'' to describe the current political regime and to warn people of what he considered an organized crime syndicate that controlled the President and 70% of all Russian money.<ref>[http://www.solzhenitsyn.ru/proizvedeniya/publizistika/rossiya_v_obvale/rossiya_v_obvale.pdf Russia under Avalanche], page 57 at the [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]]'s official website (in Russian)</ref>\n\nThe identities of seven bankers are usually taken from the original ''Financial Times'' interview with Boris Berezovsky.<ref name=clique/><ref>Daniel Treisman (2012). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=aaoSGqMw0VsC&pg=PA446&dq The Return: Russia's Journey from Gorbachev to Medvedev]''. New York: Free Press {{ISBN|978-1-4165-6071-5}}</ref><ref name=persistent/> Those include:\n#[[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]] \u2013 United Bank, [[Sibneft]], [[Channel One Russia|ORT]]\n#[[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]] \u2013 [[Bank Menatep]], [[Yukos]]\n#[[Mikhail Fridman]] \u2013 [[Alfa Group]]\n#[[Petr Aven]] \u2013 [[Alfa Group]]\n#[[Vladimir Gusinsky]] \u2013 Most Group, [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]\n#[[Vladimir Potanin]] \u2013 UNEXIM Bank\n#[[Alexander Smolensky]] \u2013 Bank Stolichny\n\nOther sources, including collective photo and video materials, suggested that [[Vladimir Vinogradov]] (Inkombank) and [[Vitaly Malkin]] ([[Rossiysky Kredit]]) were part of the closed group.<ref>Dmitry Butrin. ''[http://kommersant.ru/doc/312965 The Results of 10 Years of Capitalism]''. [[Kommersant]] newspaper, March 5, 2002 (in Russian)</ref><ref name='punch'>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ntGbeO41C5I Seven Bankers. Power Punch] at the [[TV Tsentr]] official YouTube channel, October 6, 2015 (in Russian)</ref> From then on, various sources featured different combinations of those nine names to describe the phenomenon of Semibankirschina. [[Tom Bower]] also added [[Vagit Alekperov]] to the list.<ref>[[Tom Bower]] (2010). ''[https://archive.org/details/oilmoneypolitics00bowe/page/94 Oil: Money, Politics and Power in the 21st Century]''. \u2014 New York: [[Grand Central Publishing]], p. 94-97 {{ISBN|978-0-446-56354-3}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIt is generally considered that the group was created in March 1996 when a political consultant [[Sergey Kurginyan]] invited a group of thirteen [[Russian oligarch]]s to sign the so-called ''Letter of Thirteen'' (alternatively named ''Come Out of the Dead End!'') in an attempt to cancel the [[1996 Russian presidential election|Presidential election of 1996]].<ref name='freedom'>[[Vladimir Shlapentokh]], Anna Arutunyan (2013). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=EVtsAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=letter+of+13+1996+russia+seven+bankers&source=bl&ots=gLGnCFE786&sig=pyJ5Xc4UkkPgMCIXUijHVcyRatM&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y Freedom, Repression, and Private Property in Russia]''. Cambridge: [[Cambridge University Press]] {{ISBN|9781107042148}}</ref><ref name='under'>Dmitri Butrin. ''[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/669096 The Undersigned]'' in the [[Kommersant]] newspaper, April 24, 2006 (in Russian)</ref> The manifest was published in [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] and suggested that two major candidates \u2014 Boris Yeltsin and the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation|Communist]] leader [[Gennady Zyuganov]] \u2014 should strike a \"political compromise\" in order to prevent \"the economical collapse.\" It contained eight tips that described the position of business elites. The letter was called \"a provocation\" by the Communists and thus ignored.\n\nAfter the plan failed, half of those oligarchs formed what became known as Semibankirschina \u2014 a group of seven business moguls ironically named after the 17th century [[Seven Boyars|seven boyars]] who owned the majority of Russian media resources and who decided to promote Boris Yeltsin every way possible. Since Yeltsin was highly unpopular by that time, with only 3\u20148% support, a complex technology of [[crowd manipulation]] was developed by the [[Gleb Pavlovsky]]'s and [[Marat Gelman]]'s think tank Foundation for Effective Politics,<ref name='kartofan'>Sergei Kartofanov. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20061008190755/http://www.fep.ru/publications/pr/ng290896pr.html An Approach to the President's Victory]'' by [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] \u2116 60, August 29, 1996 at the Foundation for Effective Politics website (in Russian)</ref> with the involvement of American specialists (the latter fact was used as a basis for the comedy film ''[[Spinning Boris]]'' released in 2003).\n\nKnown as an extremely \"dirty\" election campaign both inside and outside of Russia,<ref name='national'>Dimitri K. Simes. ''[http://nationalinterest.org/feature/russia-america-destined-conflict-16726?page=2 Russia and America: Destined for Conflict?]'' at [[The National Interest]], June 26, 2016</ref> it was discussed in detail in Gleb Pavlovsky's report ''President in 1996: Scenarios and Technologies of the Victory'' published shortly after. As [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] summarized it, \"the formula of victory: attracting the expert resources + dominating in the information field + blocking the competitor's moves + dominating in mass media + dominating in elites.\"<ref name='kartofan' /> The main analyst of the [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]] TV channel Vsevolod Vilchek also admitted that they actively applied technologies of mass manipulation.<ref>Viktor Martynuk. ''[http://www.km.ru/v-rossii/2012/02/22/vybory-2011-2012/medvedev-priznalsya-v-1996-m-prezidentskie-vybory-vyigral-zyuga Medvedev Confessed: In 1996 Zyuganov Won the Presidential Election]'' at KM.ru, February 22, 2012 (in Russian)</ref> Both [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] have since claimed that Yeltsin's victory was hoaxed.<ref>Simon Shuster. ''[http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2107565,00.html?xid=gonewsedit Rewriting Russian History: Did Boris Yeltsin Steal the 1996 Presidential Election?]'' at [[Time (magazine)|Time]], February 24, 2012</ref><ref>Georgi Gotev. ''[http://www.euractiv.com/section/europe-s-east/news/gorbachev-i-am-ashamed-by-putin-and-medvedev/ Gorbachev: \u2018I am ashamed by Putin and Medvedev\u2019]'' at [[EurActiv]], February 4, 2016</ref>\n\nFollowing the election, the seven bankers became the main power behind Russian politics and economy.<ref name=persistent/> Between 1996 and 2000 they gained control over the most valuable state enterprises in the natural resource and metal sectors and unofficially manipulated Yeltsin and his decisions.<ref>[[Tom Bower]] (2010). ''[https://archive.org/details/oilmoneypolitics00bowe/page/95 Oil: Money, Politics and Power in the 21st Century]''. \u2014 New York: [[Grand Central Publishing]], p. 94-97 {{ISBN|978-0-446-56354-3}}</ref><ref name='under' /> According to Boris Berezovsky, they acted through [[Anatoly Chubais]] \u2014 an architect of [[privatization in Russia]] and Yeltsin's right-hand man who granted access to him at any time.<ref name=clique/>\n\nAll this resulted in further impoverishment of the population, criminalization of businesses and the infamous [[1998 Russian financial crisis]].<ref name='punch' /> This was also the time when the word ''[[Russian oligarch|oligarch]]'' grew in popularity, substituting the ''[[New Russian]]'' [[nouveau riche]] term (both with extremely negative subtext). The 1999 saw the sudden rise to power of the unknown [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] officer [[Vladimir Putin]]. Boris Berezovsky and his associates claimed that it was him who single-handedly promoted Putin and insisted on his candidature as a Prime-minister and a President.<ref>[[Owen Matthews]]. ''[http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/03/24/how-boris-berezovsky-made-vladimir-putin-and-putin-unmade-berezovsky.html How Boris Berezovsky Made Vladimir Putin, and Putin Unmade Berezovsky]'' at [[The Daily Beast]], March 24, 2013</ref><ref>Luke Harding. ''[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/23/boris-berezovsky-vladimir-putin-feud Boris Berezovsky: a tale of revenge, betrayal and feuds with Putin]'' at [[The Guardian]], March 23, 2013</ref>\n\nYet the following years saw a quick demise of most of the seven bankers and the rise of the new generation of \"manageable\" Russian oligarchy. Khodorkovsky, Berezovsky and Gusinsky turned into [[personae non gratae]] in Russia.  Khodorkovsky lost his business as well as freedom in 2003, while Berezovsky and Gusinsky left Russia in 2000. Smolensky still owns significant companies, but lost his political influence. Vinogradov died in 2008. On 23 March 2013, Berezovsky was found dead at his home, Titness Park, at [[Sunninghill, Berkshire|Sunninghill]], near Ascot in Berkshire.<ref>''[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/23/boris-berezovsky-found-dead-berkshire-home Boris Berezovsky found dead at his Berkshire home]'' at [[The Guardian]], March 23, 2013</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Russian oligarchs]]\n*[[Boris Yeltsin presidential campaign, 1996]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/russia-bows-to-the-rule-of-the-seven-bankers-1.187734 Russia bows to the `rule of the seven bankers'] at [[The Irish Times]], August 29, 1998\n* ''Thayer Watkins''. [http://www.sjsu.edu/faculty/watkins/oligarchs.htm The Russian Oligarchs of the 1990s] at the [[San Jose State University]] website\n* [http://russiapedia.rt.com/of-russian-origin/semibankirschina/ Of Russian origin: Semibankirschina] at [[RT (TV network)|Russiapedia]]\n* [https://snob.ru/selected/entry/30178 Seven oligarchs who decided the fate of Russia] at the [[Vladimir Yakovlev (journalist)|Snob Magazine]], January 21, 2011 (in Russian)\n\n{{Boris Yeltsin}}\n\n[[Category:Russian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Russia]]\n[[Category:Boris Yeltsin 1996 presidential campaign]]\n", "text_old": "{{russianterm\n| russian = \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430\n| rusr = Semibankirschina\n| literal meaning = rule of seven bankers\n}}\n\n'''Semibankirschina''' (\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430), or seven bankers, was a group of seven [[Russia]]n [[business oligarch]]s who played an important role in the political and economical life of Russia between 1996 and 2000. In spite of internal conflicts, the group worked together in order to re-elect President [[Boris Yeltsin]] in 1996, and thereafter to successfully manipulate him and his political environment from behind the scenes.\n\nThe seven businessmen were identified by oligarch [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]] in an October 1996 interview, and the term \"semibankirschina\" was then coined by a journalist in November 1996 as a takeoff on the [[Seven Boyars]] (semiboyarschina), who deposed [[Tsar]] [[Vasili IV of Russia|Vasily Shuisky]] in 1610.\n\n==The seven bankers==\nRussian [[Russian oligarch|oligarch]] [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]], in a 29 October 1996 interview in the ''[[Financial Times]]'', named seven Russian bankers and businessmen that he claimed controlled most of the economy and media in Russia<ref name=persistent>{{cite book|last1=Bojicic-Dzelilovic|first1=Vesna|title=Persistent State Weakness in the Global Age|date=2016|publisher=[[Routledge]]|page=104|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JLgoDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA104}}</ref><ref name=clique>{{cite news|title=British Paper Names Banking Clique|url=http://old.themoscowtimes.com/sitemap/free/1996/11/article/british-paper-names-banking-clique/316590.html/|accessdate=29 March 2018|work=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=5 November 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Russia's Path PT312\"/><ref name=piratization>{{cite book|last1=Goldman|first1=Marshall I.|title=The Piratization of Russia: Russian Reform Goes Awry|date=2003|publisher=[[Routledge]]|page=132|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zP9-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA132}}</ref> and had helped bankroll [[Boris Yeltsin]]\u2019s re-election campaign in 1996.<ref name=\"FT alpha\">{{cite news| title=Mikhail Fridman: The Alpha oligarch| first1=Guy| last1=Chazan| first2=John| last2=Thornhill| url =https://www.ft.com/content/b47de3d4-c325-11e4-ac3d-00144feab7de| work=[[Financial Times]]| date=5 March 2015| accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"qui est\">{{cite news|last1=Schmouker|first1=Olivier|title=Qui est Mikhail Fridman?|url=http://www.lesaffaires.com/secteurs-d-activite/general/qui-est-mikhail-fridman-/507444|accessdate=31 March 2018|work=[[Les Affaires]]|date=9 December 2009|language=French}}</ref><ref name=\"Russia's Path PT312\">{{cite book|last1=Kotz|first1=David|last2=Weir|first2=Fred|title=Russia's Path from Gorbachev to Putin: The Demise of the Soviet System and the New Russia|date=2007|publisher=[[Routledge]]|page=218|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=20OUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT312}}</ref><ref name=piratization/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lloyd|first1=John|title=The Autumn Of the Oligarchs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/08/magazine/the-autumn-of-the-oligarchs.html|accessdate=30 March 2018|work=[[New York Times]]|date=8 October 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe word \"Semibankirschina\" was subsequently coined by the Russian journalist Andrey Fadin of the ''Obschaya Gazeta'' newspaper, in a 14 November 1996 article titled \"Semibankirschina as a New Russian Variation of Semiboyarschina\".<ref>[http://kommersant.ru/doc/390624 Semibankirschina as a New Russian Variation of Semiboyarschina] fragment in the [[Kommersant]] newspaper, June 23, 2003 (in Russian)</ref> He wrote that \"they control the access to budget money and basically all investment opportunities inside the country. They own the gigantic information resource of the major TV channels. They form the President's opinion. Those who didn't want to walk along them were either strangled or left the circle.\" Slightly over a year later, Fadin was killed in a car accident.<ref>Sergei Mitrofanov. ''[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/188217 Journalist Andrei Fadin died]''. [[Kommersant]] newspaper, November 22, 1997 (in Russian)</ref> [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]] also used this word in his critical 1998 essay ''Russia under Avalanche'' to describe the current political regime and to warn people of what he considered an organized crime syndicate that controlled the President and 70% of all Russian money.<ref>[http://www.solzhenitsyn.ru/proizvedeniya/publizistika/rossiya_v_obvale/rossiya_v_obvale.pdf Russia under Avalanche], page 57 at the [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]]'s official website (in Russian)</ref>\n\nThe identities of seven bankers are usually taken from the original ''Financial Times'' interview with Boris Berezovsky.<ref name=clique/><ref>Daniel Treisman (2012). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=aaoSGqMw0VsC&pg=PA446&dq The Return: Russia's Journey from Gorbachev to Medvedev]''. New York: Free Press {{ISBN|978-1-4165-6071-5}}</ref><ref name=persistent/> Those include:\n#[[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]] \u2013 United Bank, [[Sibneft]], [[Channel One Russia|ORT]]\n#[[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]] \u2013 [[Bank Menatep]], [[Yukos]]\n#[[Mikhail Fridman]] \u2013 [[Alfa Group]]\n#[[Petr Aven]] \u2013 [[Alfa Group]]\n#[[Vladimir Gusinsky]] \u2013 Most Group, [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]\n#[[Vladimir Potanin]] \u2013 UNEXIM Bank\n#[[Alexander Smolensky]] \u2013 Bank Stolichny\n\nOther sources, including collective photo and video materials, suggested that [[Vladimir Vinogradov]] (Inkombank) and [[Vitaly Malkin]] ([[Rossiysky Kredit]]) were part of the closed group.<ref>Dmitry Butrin. ''[http://kommersant.ru/doc/312965 The Results of 10 Years of Capitalism]''. [[Kommersant]] newspaper, March 5, 2002 (in Russian)</ref><ref name='punch'>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ntGbeO41C5I Seven Bankers. Power Punch] at the [[TV Tsentr]] official YouTube channel, October 6, 2015 (in Russian)</ref> From then on, various sources featured different combinations of those nine names to describe the phenomenon of Semibankirschina. [[Tom Bower]] also added [[Vagit Alekperov]] to the list.<ref>[[Tom Bower]] (2010). ''[https://archive.org/details/oilmoneypolitics00bowe/page/94 Oil: Money, Politics and Power in the 21st Century]''. \u2014 New York: [[Grand Central Publishing]], p. 94-97 {{ISBN|978-0-446-56354-3}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIt is generally considered that the group was created in March 1996 when a political consultant [[Sergey Kurginyan]] invited a group of thirteen [[Russian oligarch]]s to sign the so-called ''Letter of Thirteen'' (alternatively named ''Come Out of the Dead End!'') in an attempt to cancel the [[1996 Russian presidential election|Presidential election of 1996]].<ref name='freedom'>[[Vladimir Shlapentokh]], Anna Arutunyan (2013). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=EVtsAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=letter+of+13+1996+russia+seven+bankers&source=bl&ots=gLGnCFE786&sig=pyJ5Xc4UkkPgMCIXUijHVcyRatM&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y Freedom, Repression, and Private Property in Russia]''. Cambridge: [[Cambridge University Press]] {{ISBN|9781107042148}}</ref><ref name='under'>Dmitri Butrin. ''[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/669096 The Undersigned]'' in the [[Kommersant]] newspaper, April 24, 2006 (in Russian)</ref> The manifest was published in [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] and suggested that two major candidates \u2014 Boris Yeltsin and the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation|Communist]] leader [[Gennady Zyuganov]] \u2014 should strike a \"political compromise\" in order to prevent \"the economical collapse.\" It contained eight tips that described the position of business elites. The letter was called \"a provocation\" by the Communists and thus ignored.\n\nAfter the plan failed, half of those oligarchs formed what became known as Semibankirschina \u2014 a group of seven business moguls ironically named after the 17th century [[Seven Boyars|seven boyars]] who owned the majority of Russian media resources and who decided to promote Boris Yeltsin every way possible. Since Yeltsin was highly unpopular by that time, with only 3\u20148% support, a complex technology of [[crowd manipulation]] was developed by the [[Gleb Pavlovsky]]'s and [[Marat Gelman]]'s think tank Foundation for Effective Politics,<ref name='kartofan'>Sergei Kartofanov. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20061008190755/http://www.fep.ru/publications/pr/ng290896pr.html An Approach to the President's Victory]'' by [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] \u2116 60, August 29, 1996 at the Foundation for Effective Politics website (in Russian)</ref> with the involvement of American specialists (the latter fact was used as a basis for the comedy film ''[[Spinning Boris]]'' released in 2003).\n\nKnown as an extremely \"dirty\" election campaign both inside and outside of Russia,<ref name='national'>Dimitri K. Simes. ''[http://nationalinterest.org/feature/russia-america-destined-conflict-16726?page=2 Russia and America: Destined for Conflict?]'' at [[The National Interest]], June 26, 2016</ref> it was discussed in detail in Gleb Pavlovsky's report ''President in 1996: Scenarios and Technologies of the Victory'' published shortly after. As [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] summarized it, \"the formula of victory: attracting the expert resources + dominating in the information field + blocking the competitor's moves + dominating in mass media + dominating in elites.\"<ref name='kartofan' /> The main analyst of the [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]] TV channel Vsevolod Vilchek also admitted that they actively applied technologies of mass manipulation.<ref>Viktor Martynuk. ''[http://www.km.ru/v-rossii/2012/02/22/vybory-2011-2012/medvedev-priznalsya-v-1996-m-prezidentskie-vybory-vyigral-zyuga Medvedev Confessed: In 1996 Zyuganov Won the Presidential Election]'' at KM.ru, February 22, 2012 (in Russian)</ref> Both [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] have since claimed that Yeltsin's victory was hoaxed.<ref>Simon Shuster. ''[http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2107565,00.html?xid=gonewsedit Rewriting Russian History: Did Boris Yeltsin Steal the 1996 Presidential Election?]'' at [[Time (magazine)|Time]], February 24, 2012</ref><ref>Georgi Gotev. ''[http://www.euractiv.com/section/europe-s-east/news/gorbachev-i-am-ashamed-by-putin-and-medvedev/ Gorbachev: \u2018I am ashamed by Putin and Medvedev\u2019]'' at [[EurActiv]], February 4, 2016</ref>\n\nFollowing the election, the seven bankers became the main power behind Russian politics and economy.<ref name=persistent/> Between 1996 and 2000 they gained control over the most valuable state enterprises in the natural resource and metal sectors and unofficially manipulated Yeltsin and his decisions.<ref>[[Tom Bower]] (2010). ''[https://archive.org/details/oilmoneypolitics00bowe/page/95 Oil: Money, Politics and Power in the 21st Century]''. \u2014 New York: [[Grand Central Publishing]], p. 94-97 {{ISBN|978-0-446-56354-3}}</ref><ref name='under' /> According to Boris Berezovsky, they acted through [[Anatoly Chubais]] \u2014 an architect of [[privatization in Russia]] and Yeltsin's right-hand man who granted access to him at any time.<ref name=clique/>\n\nAll this resulted in further impoverishment of the population, criminalization of businesses and the infamous [[1998 Russian financial crisis]].<ref name='punch' /> This was also the time when the word ''[[Russian oligarch|oligarch]]'' grew in popularity, substituting the ''[[New Russian]]'' [[nouveau riche]] term (both with extremely negative subtext). The 1999 saw the sudden rise to power of the unknown [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] officer [[Vladimir Putin]]. Boris Berezovsky and his associates claimed that it was him who single-handedly promoted Putin and insisted on his candidature as a Prime-minister and a President.<ref>[[Owen Matthews]]. ''[http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/03/24/how-boris-berezovsky-made-vladimir-putin-and-putin-unmade-berezovsky.html How Boris Berezovsky Made Vladimir Putin, and Putin Unmade Berezovsky]'' at [[The Daily Beast]], March 24, 2013</ref><ref>Luke Harding. ''[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/23/boris-berezovsky-vladimir-putin-feud Boris Berezovsky: a tale of revenge, betrayal and feuds with Putin]'' at [[The Guardian]], March 23, 2013</ref>\n\nYet the following years saw a quick demise of most of the seven bankers and the rise of the new generation of \"manageable\" Russian oligarchy. Khodorkovsky, Berezovsky and Gusinsky turned into [[personae non gratae]] in Russia.  Khodorkovsky lost his business as well as freedom in 2003, while Berezovsky and Gusinsky left Russia in 2000. Smolensky still owns significant companies, but lost his political influence. Vinogradov died in 2008. On 23 March 2013, Berezovsky was found dead at his home, Titness Park, at [[Sunninghill, Berkshire|Sunninghill]], near Ascot in Berkshire.<ref>''[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/23/boris-berezovsky-found-dead-berkshire-home Boris Berezovsky found dead at his Berkshire home]'' at [[The Guardian]], March 23, 2013</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Russian oligarchs]]\n*[[Boris Yeltsin presidential campaign, 1996]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/russia-bows-to-the-rule-of-the-seven-bankers-1.187734 Russia bows to the `rule of the seven bankers'] at [[The Irish Times]], August 29, 1998\n* ''Thayer Watkins''. [http://www.sjsu.edu/faculty/watkins/oligarchs.htm The Russian Oligarchs of the 1990's] at the [[San Jose State University]] website\n* [http://russiapedia.rt.com/of-russian-origin/semibankirschina/ Of Russian origin: Semibankirschina] at [[RT (TV network)|Russiapedia]]\n* [https://snob.ru/selected/entry/30178 Seven oligarchs who decided the fate of Russia] at the [[Vladimir Yakovlev (journalist)|Snob Magazine]], January 21, 2011 (in Russian)\n\n{{Boris Yeltsin}}\n\n[[Category:Russian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Russia]]\n[[Category:Boris Yeltsin 1996 presidential campaign]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semibankirschina"}
{"title_page": "Avery Sharpe", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               = Avery Sharpe\n| image              = Louis Hayes AverySharpe McCoyTyner.jpg\n| image_size       =\n| landscape         =\n| caption             =McCoy Tyner - Avery Sharpe - Louis Hayes (Berlin 1987)\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Avery George Sharpe\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1954|8|23}}\n| birth_place        =[[Valdosta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre               = Jazz\n| occupation        = Musician\n| instrument        = Double bass\n| years_active     =1970s\u2013present\n| label                =JKNM\n| associated_acts =[[McCoy Tyner]]\n| website            = {{URL|averysharpe.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Avery Sharpe''' (born August 23, 1954) is an American [[jazz]] [[double-bass]]ist,  electric bassist, composer, educator and founder of the artist owned record label, JKNM Records, back in 1993.\n\nSharpe has a distinguished percussive and rhythmic approach on double bass and is something to see in live performances. He incorporates the Hum-a-long(vocal scatting with the bowed bass) bass technique, popularized by Leroy \u201cSlam\u201d Stewart and Major \u201cMule\u201d Holly, into his playing.\n\nSharpe was first bought to prominence by tenor saxophonist [[Archie Shepp]] and drummer [[Art Blakey]], but is best known for his longtime association with Piano Jazz Legend [[McCoy Tyner]] from 1980-2003. He recorded some 20 plus records with Tyner.\n\n== Early Life ==\nSharpe's first instrument was the piano, which he started playing at eight years old.  His mother, Evelyn was a pianist and choir director in the Church of God in Christ (COGIC) and she gave lessons to Sharpe, as well as to his 7 other siblings. Sharpe also studied the accordion, in his youth and ultimately the electric bass. While attending the University of Massahusetts, (Amherst) Sharpe studied double bass with Reggie Workman. While at UMASS, he also studied with Max Roach, Archie Shepp, Horace Boyer and Fred Tillis. He played the double and electric bass in gospel, funk, rock groups, jazz band and orchestra, while there. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.williams.edu/profile/ags3/|title=Avery G. Sharpe {{!}} Music|website=music.williams.edu|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nHe has also played as a sideman with [[Archie Shepp]], [[Yusef Lateef]], [[Ricky Ford]], [[Joe Ford (musician)|Joe Ford]], and others. As a leader, he has  released on [[Sunnyside Records]], and several albums on his own label, JKNM. Avery Sharpe has multiple roles at [[Williams College]], as an Artist Associate and Jazz Coach<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.williams.edu/profile/ags3/www.averysharpe.com|title=Avery G. Sharpe {{!}} Music|website=music.williams.edu|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>. Sharpe also serves additional roles at Williams College; as Faculty Advisor for the Williams Gospel Choir<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.williams.edu/ensembles/gospel-choir/|title=Gospel Choir|last=Center|first=Williams College : Music Bernhard Music|last2=Williamstown|first2=54 Chapin Hall Drive|website=Music|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13|last3=fax: 413.597.3100|first3=MA 01267 USA tel: 413 597 2127 {{!}}}}</ref> and as affiliation with the Africana Studies department<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africana-studies.williams.edu/faculty/affiliated-facultystaff/|title=Affiliated Faculty/Staff|website=Africana Studies|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nSharpe\u2019s parents James and Evelyn (Green) Sharpe had 8 children and Avery is number 6. He married his high School sweetheart Cheryl(Scott) after college and they have 4 Children. He is a health enthusiast and has promoted Vegan/plant based lifestyle and physical training since 1977.\n\n== Compositions ==\nIn 1989, he wrote and conducted the soundtrack for the movie An Unremarkable Life<ref>{{Citation|title=An Unremarkable Life (1989)|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/us/film708962.html|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>.\u00a0 In the 1990s, Sharpe was commissioned by Fideleo to write three extended works<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sherman|first=Robert|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/26/nyregion/music-the-flight-plan-rachmaninoff.html|title=MUSIC; The Flight Plan: Rachmaninoff|date=2003-01-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. In 2004, Sharpe\u00a0wrote a musical portrait for the stage for Chamber Music Plus. Sharpe (as well as actress Jasmine Guy), are featured in the stage production of Raisin\u2019 Cane<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opus.govst.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?filename=0&article=1274&context=cpa_memorabilia&type=additional&usg=AOvVaw3jz2pQ6bRWQ8ERf6iAQ22h|title=Raisin' Cane Playbill|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nSharpe\u2019s composition \u201cJanuary in Brazil\u2019 is on McCoy Tyner\u2019s Grammy award winning big band album \u201cJourney\u201d\n\nSharpe has been commissioned by the Springfield Symphony Orchestra on multiple occasions. Sharpe debuted his six-movement piece America\u2019s Promise with the Springfield Symphony Orchestra. In 2006, Sharpe was commissioned to write a Concerto for Jazz Trio and Orchestra, which premiered in 2007 with [[Kevin Eubanks]] on acoustic guitar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forbassplayersonly.com/interview-avery-sharpe/|title=Avery Sharpe|date=2009-09-21|website=For Bass Players Only|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== 400: An African American Musical Portrait ==\n[[File:Avery litchfield jazz festival 2013 Avery Sharpe group.jpg|thumb|Sharpe at the Litchfield Jazz Festival in 2013]]\nSharpe released an album in 2019 titled \"400: An African American Musical Portrait,\" which is in reference to the 400<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the first African slaves were brought to Jamestown, Virginia in 1619 by the Dutch. The album utilizes many styles, to feature the African American musical tradition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/400-an-african-american-musical-portrait-avery-sharpe-jknm-records-review-by-troy-dostert.php|title=Avery Sharpe: 400: An African American Musical Portrait album review @ All About Jazz|last=Jazz|first=All About|website=All About Jazz|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nSharpe has been awarded the NAACP Martin Luther King Jr Special Achievement Award, National Endowment for the Arts Grants and the New England Foundation for the Arts Achievement in Jazz Award (1997). \n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n* ''Unspoken Words'' ([[Sunnyside Records|Sunnyside]], 1988)\n* ''Extended Family'' (JKNM, 1993)\n* ''Extended Family, Vol. 2: Thoughts of My Ancestors'' (JKNM, 1995)\n* ''Extended Family, Vol. 3: Family Values'' (JKNM, 2001)\n* ''Dragon Fly'' (JKNM, 2005)\n* ''Epic Ebony Journey'' (JKNM, 2005)\n* ''Legends and Mentors'' (JKNM, 2008)\n* ''Autumn Moonlight'' (JKNM, 2009)\n* ''Avery Sharpe Trio Live'' (JKNM, 2010)\n* ''Raisn' Cane (musical excerpts from the play with Jasmine Guy and the Avery Sharpe Trio)'' (JKNM, 2010)\n* ''Running Man'' (JKNM, 2011)\n* ''Sojourner Truth \u201c. . . ain\u2019t I a woman?\u201d '' (JKNM, 2012)\n*''Sharpe Meets Tharpe- A tribute to Sister Rosett'' (JKNM, 2016)\n*''400: An African American Musical Portrait'' (JKNM, 2019)\n\n'''With [[McCoy Tyner]]'''\n* La Leyenda de La Hora (the legend of the hour) 1981\n*''[[Just Feelin']]''  (1985)\n* ''[[Double Trios]]''  (1986)\n* ''[[Major Changes]]''  (1987)\n* ''[[Bon Voyage (McCoy Tyner album)|Bon Voyage]]''  (1987)\n* ''[[Live at the Musicians Exchange Cafe]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Uptown/Downtown]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Solar: Live at Sweet Basil]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Blue Bossa (McCoy Tyner album)|Blue Bossa]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Remembering John]]'' (1991)\n*McCoy Tyner / Sir Roland Hanna* \u2013 Double Exposure (1992)\n*\"Key of Sol\"-Live at Sweet Basil (1991)\n* ''[[Journey (McCoy Tyner album)|Journey]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Infinity (McCoy Tyner album)|Infinity]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Autumn Mood]]'' (1997)\n*McCoy Tyner and the Latin All-Stars (1999)\n\n'''With [[Yusef Lateef]]'''\n\n* Tenors of Yusef Lateef and Archie Shepp(YAL, 1992)\n*Yusef Lateef Plays Ballads (YAL, 1992)\n*''Tenors featuring Rene McLean (YAL, 1993)''\n*''Yusef Lateef and Ralph M. Jones III, Woodwinds (YAL,1993)''\n*''Yusef Lateef Metamorphosis(YAL, 1993)''\n*''[[Tenors of Yusef Lateef & Ricky Ford]]'' (YAL, 1994) with [[Ricky Ford]]\n*Full Circle Yusef Lateef (YAL, 1996)\n*''CHNOPS: Gold & Soul Yusef Lateef (YAL, 1997)''\n\n'''With Archie Shepp'''\n\n* Archie Shepp \"Attica Blues-Live at Palais des Glaces\"-(Blue Marge Record, 1979)\n* Archie Shepp-The Good Life(Black and Blue, 1984)\n\n'''With Frank Morgan'''\n\n* \"Major Changes\"-Contemporary Records(1987)\n\n'''With John Blake'''\n\n* \"Twinkling of an Eye\"-Grammavision(1985)\n\n'''With David Matthews'''\n\n* \"Jazz Ballads with Strings\"-Alfa Records(1991)\n\n'''With Steve Grossman'''\n\n* \"In New York\"-Disques Dreyfus(1991)\n\n'''With Vacca/Moran'''\n\n* \"Dance Beneath the Diamond Sky\"-Columbia Records(1992)\n\n'''With Jeri Brown'''\n\n* \"Fresh Start\"-Just In Time Records(1996)\n* \u201cZaius\u201d-Just In Time Records(1998)\n* \u201cI\u2019ve Got Your Number\u201d- Just In Time Records(1999)\n* The Image in the Mirror-Tryptec\u201d-Just In Time Records(2001)\n* \u201c Firm Roots\u201d-Just In Time Records(2003)\n\n'''With Marc Puricelli'''\n\n* \"The Shade\"-Music Masters(1996)\n* \"Melting Point\"-Music Masters(1994)\n* \u201cDesire\u201d-Music Masters\n\n'''With Chico Freeman'''\n\n* \u201cOh By the Way\u201d Quataca(Double Moon Records,2001)\n\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p11673/biography|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharpe, Avery}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:American jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               = Avery Sharpe\n| image              = Louis Hayes AverySharpe McCoyTyner.jpg\n| image_size       =\n| landscape         =\n| caption             =McCoy Tyner - Avery Sharpe - Louis Hayes (Berlin 1987)\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Avery George Sharpe\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1954|8|23}}\n| birth_place        =[[Valdosta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre               = Jazz\n| occupation        = Musician\n| instrument        = Double bass\n| years_active     =1970s\u2013present\n| label                =JKNM\n| associated_acts =[[McCoy Tyner]]\n| website            = {{URL|averysharpe.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Avery Sharpe''' (born August 23, 1954) is an American [[jazz]] [[double-bass]]ist,  electric bassist, composer, educator and founder of the artist owned record label, JKNM Records, back in 1993.\n\nSharpe has a distinguished percussive and rhythmic approach on double bass and is something to see in live performances. He incorporates the Hum-a-long(vocal scatting with the bowed bass) bass technique, popularized by Leroy \u201cSlam\u201d Stewart and Major \u201cMule\u201d Holly, into his playing.\n\nSharpe was first bought to prominence by tenor saxophonist [[Archie Shepp]] and drummer [[Art Blakey]], but is best known for his longtime association with Piano Jazz Legend [[McCoy Tyner]] from 1980-2003. He recorded some 20 plus records with Tyner.\n\n== Early Life ==\nSharpe's first instrument was the piano, which he started playing at eight years old.  His mother, Evelyn was a pianist and choir director in the Church of God in Christ (COGIC) and she gave lessons to Sharpe, as well as to his 7 other siblings. Sharpe also studied the accordion, in his youth and ultimately the electric bass. While attending the University of Massahusetts, (Amherst) Sharpe studied double bass with Reggie Workman. While at UMASS, he also studied with Max Roach, Archie Shepp, Horace Boyer and Fred Tillis. He played the double and electric bass in gospel, funk, rock groups, jazz band and orchestra, while there. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.williams.edu/profile/ags3/|title=Avery G. Sharpe {{!}} Music|website=music.williams.edu|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nHe has also played as a sideman with [[Archie Shepp]], [[Yusef Lateef]], [[Ricky Ford]], [[Joe Ford (musician)|Joe Ford]], and others. As a leader, he has  released on [[Sunnyside Records]], and several albums on his own label, JKNM. Avery Sharpe has multiple roles at [[Williams College]], as an Artist Associate and Jazz Coach<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.williams.edu/profile/ags3/www.averysharpe.com|title=Avery G. Sharpe {{!}} Music|website=music.williams.edu|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>. Sharpe also serves additional roles at Williams College; as Faculty Advisor for the Williams Gospel Choir<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.williams.edu/ensembles/gospel-choir/|title=Gospel Choir|last=Center|first=Williams College : Music Bernhard Music|last2=Williamstown|first2=54 Chapin Hall Drive|website=Music|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13|last3=fax: 413.597.3100|first3=MA 01267 USA tel: 413 597 2127 {{!}}}}</ref> and as affiliation with the Africana Studies department<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africana-studies.williams.edu/faculty/affiliated-facultystaff/|title=Affiliated Faculty/Staff|website=Africana Studies|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nSharpe\u2019s parents James and Evelyn (Green) Sharpe had 8 children and Avery is number 6. He married his high School sweetheart Cheryl(Scott) after college and they have 4 Children. He is a health enthusiast and has promoted Vegan/plant based lifestyle and physical training since 1977.\n\n== Compositions ==\nIn 1989, he wrote and conducted the soundtrack for the movie An Unremarkable Life<ref>{{Citation|title=An Unremarkable Life (1989)|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/us/film708962.html|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>.\u00a0 In the 1990\u2019s, Sharpe was commissioned by Fideleo to write three extended works<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sherman|first=Robert|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/26/nyregion/music-the-flight-plan-rachmaninoff.html|title=MUSIC; The Flight Plan: Rachmaninoff|date=2003-01-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. In 2004, Sharpe\u00a0wrote a musical portrait for the stage for Chamber Music Plus. Sharpe (as well as actress Jasmine Guy), are featured in the stage production of Raisin\u2019 Cane<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opus.govst.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?filename=0&article=1274&context=cpa_memorabilia&type=additional&usg=AOvVaw3jz2pQ6bRWQ8ERf6iAQ22h|title=Raisin' Cane Playbill|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nSharpe\u2019s composition \u201cJanuary in Brazil\u2019 is on McCoy Tyner\u2019s Grammy award winning big band album \u201cJourney\u201d\n\nSharpe has been commissioned by the Springfield Symphony Orchestra on multiple occasions. Sharpe debuted his six-movement piece America\u2019s Promise with the Springfield Symphony Orchestra. In 2006, Sharpe was commissioned to write a Concerto for Jazz Trio and Orchestra, which premiered in 2007 with [[Kevin Eubanks]] on acoustic guitar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forbassplayersonly.com/interview-avery-sharpe/|title=Avery Sharpe|date=2009-09-21|website=For Bass Players Only|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== 400: An African American Musical Portrait ==\n[[File:Avery litchfield jazz festival 2013 Avery Sharpe group.jpg|thumb|Sharpe at the Litchfield Jazz Festival in 2013]]\nSharpe released an album in 2019 titled \"400: An African American Musical Portrait,\" which is in reference to the 400<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the first African slaves were brought to Jamestown, Virginia in 1619 by the Dutch. The album utilizes many styles, to feature the African American musical tradition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/400-an-african-american-musical-portrait-avery-sharpe-jknm-records-review-by-troy-dostert.php|title=Avery Sharpe: 400: An African American Musical Portrait album review @ All About Jazz|last=Jazz|first=All About|website=All About Jazz|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nSharpe has been awarded the NAACP Martin Luther King Jr Special Achievement Award, National Endowment for the Arts Grants and the New England Foundation for the Arts Achievement in Jazz Award (1997). \n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n* ''Unspoken Words'' ([[Sunnyside Records|Sunnyside]], 1988)\n* ''Extended Family'' (JKNM, 1993)\n* ''Extended Family, Vol. 2: Thoughts of My Ancestors'' (JKNM, 1995)\n* ''Extended Family, Vol. 3: Family Values'' (JKNM, 2001)\n* ''Dragon Fly'' (JKNM, 2005)\n* ''Epic Ebony Journey'' (JKNM, 2005)\n* ''Legends and Mentors'' (JKNM, 2008)\n* ''Autumn Moonlight'' (JKNM, 2009)\n* ''Avery Sharpe Trio Live'' (JKNM, 2010)\n* ''Raisn' Cane (musical excerpts from the play with Jasmine Guy and the Avery Sharpe Trio)'' (JKNM, 2010)\n* ''Running Man'' (JKNM, 2011)\n* ''Sojourner Truth \u201c. . . ain\u2019t I a woman?\u201d '' (JKNM, 2012)\n*''Sharpe Meets Tharpe- A tribute to Sister Rosett'' (JKNM, 2016)\n*''400: An African American Musical Portrait'' (JKNM, 2019)\n\n'''With [[McCoy Tyner]]'''\n* La Leyenda de La Hora (the legend of the hour) 1981\n*''[[Just Feelin']]''  (1985)\n* ''[[Double Trios]]''  (1986)\n* ''[[Major Changes]]''  (1987)\n* ''[[Bon Voyage (McCoy Tyner album)|Bon Voyage]]''  (1987)\n* ''[[Live at the Musicians Exchange Cafe]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Uptown/Downtown]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Solar: Live at Sweet Basil]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Blue Bossa (McCoy Tyner album)|Blue Bossa]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Remembering John]]'' (1991)\n*McCoy Tyner / Sir Roland Hanna* \u2013 Double Exposure (1992)\n*\"Key of Sol\"-Live at Sweet Basil (1991)\n* ''[[Journey (McCoy Tyner album)|Journey]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Infinity (McCoy Tyner album)|Infinity]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Autumn Mood]]'' (1997)\n*McCoy Tyner and the Latin All-Stars (1999)\n\n'''With [[Yusef Lateef]]'''\n\n* Tenors of Yusef Lateef and Archie Shepp(YAL, 1992)\n*Yusef Lateef Plays Ballads (YAL, 1992)\n*''Tenors featuring Rene McLean (YAL, 1993)''\n*''Yusef Lateef and Ralph M. Jones III, Woodwinds (YAL,1993)''\n*''Yusef Lateef Metamorphosis(YAL, 1993)''\n*''[[Tenors of Yusef Lateef & Ricky Ford]]'' (YAL, 1994) with [[Ricky Ford]]\n*Full Circle Yusef Lateef (YAL, 1996)\n*''CHNOPS: Gold & Soul Yusef Lateef (YAL, 1997)''\n\n'''With Archie Shepp'''\n\n* Archie Shepp \"Attica Blues-Live at Palais des Glaces\"-(Blue Marge Record, 1979)\n* Archie Shepp-The Good Life(Black and Blue, 1984)\n\n'''With Frank Morgan'''\n\n* \"Major Changes\"-Contemporary Records(1987)\n\n'''With John Blake'''\n\n* \"Twinkling of an Eye\"-Grammavision(1985)\n\n'''With David Matthews'''\n\n* \"Jazz Ballads with Strings\"-Alfa Records(1991)\n\n'''With Steve Grossman'''\n\n* \"In New York\"-Disques Dreyfus(1991)\n\n'''With Vacca/Moran'''\n\n* \"Dance Beneath the Diamond Sky\"-Columbia Records(1992)\n\n'''With Jeri Brown'''\n\n* \"Fresh Start\"-Just In Time Records(1996)\n* \u201cZaius\u201d-Just In Time Records(1998)\n* \u201cI\u2019ve Got Your Number\u201d- Just In Time Records(1999)\n* The Image in the Mirror-Tryptec\u201d-Just In Time Records(2001)\n* \u201c Firm Roots\u201d-Just In Time Records(2003)\n\n'''With Marc Puricelli'''\n\n* \"The Shade\"-Music Masters(1996)\n* \"Melting Point\"-Music Masters(1994)\n* \u201cDesire\u201d-Music Masters\n\n'''With Chico Freeman'''\n\n* \u201cOh By the Way\u201d Quataca(Double Moon Records,2001)\n\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p11673/bio