on of organized violence against civilians. It appeared in the 1960s, committed by [[communist]] guerrillas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://luchadeclasesyprocesohistorico.blogspot.com/2011/12/breve-cronologia-de-los-principales.html|title=Breve cronolog\u00eda de los principales movimientos sociales ocurridos en M\u00e9xico|work=Lucha de Clases.org|accessdate=2018-08-08}}</ref> Later attacks were by other political movements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cnsnews.com/news/article/hillary-clinton-iran-exports-terrorism-mexico|title=Hillary Clinton: Iran 'Exports Terrorism' to Mexicowork=CNN|accessdate=2018-08-08}}</ref>\n\n==Far Left Groups==\n[[image:L'ex\u00e8rcit al carrer 30 de juliol.jpg|thumbnail|right|Soldiers of the Mexican Army in the streets]]\n[[File:Guerrilleros del TDR-EP.jpg|thumb|left|TDR-EP guerrillas during a revolutionary meeting]]\n\nMain article; [[Dirty War (Mexico)|Dirty war in M\u00e9xico]], [[Chiapas conflict]]\n\nFrom the late 1960s to the 1980\u00b4s guerrilla movements operated in the country. The worst attacks were the assault of the Madera Cuartel and [[Tlatelolco Massacre]], the starting point for several guerrilla movements, specially in the states of [[Guerrero]] and [[Ciudad de Mexico]]. Groups included [[Party of the Poor (Mexico)|Partido de los Pobres]], [[People's Guerrilla Group]], or [[Liga Comunista 23 de Septiembre]]. These groups were demolished, amid allegations of extrajudicial executions or forced disappearances.<ref>{{Cite book|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=aeaN27DJ3m0C}}|title=El enemigo interno: contrainsurgencia y fuerzas armadas en M\u00e9xico|last=Guzm\u00e1n|first=Jorge Luis Sierra|date=2003|publisher=Plaza y Valdes|isbn=9789707221963|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Introducci\u00f3n a la historia de la guerrilla en M\u00e9xico. 1943-1983. by Juan Fernando Reyes Pel\u00e1ez (Paperback)|last=|first=|date=February 26, 2008|publisher=Juan Fernando Reyes Pel\u00e1ez|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=es|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEventually in the 1990\u00b4s the guerrilla activity it would focus in states of [[Guerrero]] , [[Oaxaca]] (with bastions of the [[Ejercito Popular Revolucionario]], [[:es:Ej\u00e9rcito Revolucionario del Pueblo Insurgente|Ej\u00e9rcito Revolucionario del Pueblo Insurgente]] and [[:es:Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias del Pueblo|Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias del Pueblo]], [[:es:Tendencia Democr\u00e1tica Revolucionaria-Ej\u00e9rcito del Pueblo|Tendencia Democr\u00e1tica Revolucionaria-Ej\u00e9rcito del Pueblo]], \nthese last splits of the EPR)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.contralinea.com.mx/archivo-revista/2013/05/03/jacobo-silva-el-nacimiento-del-erpi/|title=Jacobo Silva: el nacimiento del ERPI|work=Contralinea|accessdate=2019-05-06}}</ref> and [[Chiapas]] this one gaining relevance with the [[Ejercito Zapatista De Liberacion Nacional]]\n\n==Narcoterrorism==\n{{Main article|Mexican Drug War}}\n\nIn 2012 United States politician [[Sue Myrick]] claimed that mounting evidence of [[Hezbollah]] presence in Mexico was ignored by the [[Department of Homeland Security]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/10/29/lawmaker-urges-feds-to-monitor-hezbollah-in-mexico/ | work=Fox News | title=Lawmaker urges feds to monitor Hezbollah in Mexico | date=2012-10-29 | accessdate=2012-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/opinion/mauricio-meschoulam/hezbollah-en-mexico|title=\u00bfHezbollah en M\u00e9xico? (In Spanish)|work=El Universal|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref>\nThese groups became more visible by 2010, when the Tucson Police Department reported International Terrorism Situational Awareness for [[Hezbollah]] in Mexico, noting the arrest of Jameel Nasar in [[Tijuana]]. Nasar had tried to form a Hezbollah network in Mexico and [[South America]]. A report from the US [[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|House Homeland Security Committee]] Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations and Management tied Middle East terror organizations with Mexican drug cartels.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/opinion/raymundo-riva-palacio/hezbola-en-mexico|title=Hezbol\u00e1 en M\u00e9xico (In Spanish)|work=El Financiero|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/opinion/walter-astie-burgos/narcoterrorismo|title=\u00bfNarcoterrorismo? (In Spanish)|work=El Universal|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nCurrently the violence related with the [[Mexican Drug War|drug war]] represents the conflict of greatest generation of violence in the country, causing some attacks that can be branded as narco-terrorism like [[2008 Morelia grenade attacks]], [[2009 Guanajuato and Hidalgo shootings]] and the [[2011 Monterrey casino attack]] or the recently [[Minatitl\u00e1n shooting]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://justiceinmexico.org/data/|title=Justice in MexicO/Data Base|work=Justice in Mexico|accessdate=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n==Anarchist Groups==\nAnarchist groups in M\u00e9xico have been on the rise since the beginning of the 2000s, with a large number of attacks to banks, religious centers and government buildings, especially intensifying during the government of [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milenio.com/policia/la-directriz-anarquista-contra-objetivos-humanos|title=La directriz anarquista contra \"objetivos humanos\"|work=Grupo Milenio|accessdate=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milenio.com/policia/lo-que-los-anarquistas-quieren-en-sus-palabras|title=Lo que los anarquistas quieren, en sus palabras... (In Spanish)|work=Milenio|accessdate=2019-06-05}}</ref> Groups like C\u00e9lulas Aut\u00f3nomas de Revoluci\u00f3n Inmediata-Praxedis G. Guerrero, C\u00e9lula Insurreccional Mariano Sanchez A\u00f1\u00f3n, Brigada Informal Bruno Filippi, [[:es:Individualistas Tendiendo a lo Salvaje|Individualistas Tendiendo a lo Salvaje]], and others. The most notorious incident with this group was the [[Monterrey Tech bombing]].\n\nIn 2017 the [[CISEN]] (the mexican civil intelligence institution at the service of the government of Mexico) said that these \"direct violent actions\" came from groups such as the [[Earth Liberation Front]] (52 actions), the [[Animal Liberation Front]] (44), Celulas Aut\u00f3nomas de Revoluci\u00f3n Inmediata-Pr\u00e1xedis Guerrero (32), [[Federazione Anarchia Informale]] (30) and the Conspiracy of Fire Cells (12). In [[Mexico City]], the Cisen documented the existence of the Campamento Revoluci\u00f3n,Bloque Anarko Sur (responsible for assaulting a group of journalists during a demonstration in 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homozapping.com.mx/2014/06/documentan-agresiones-contra-periodistas-volveran-a-ser-abatidos-aseguran-anarquistas/|title=Documentan agresiones contra periodistas; \"volver\u00e1n a ser abatidos\", aseguran anarquistas (In Spanish)|work=Homozapping|accessdate=2019-09-25}}</ref>, the Anarko Norte Bloc, the Black Anarchist Bloc, the Chanti Oll\u00edn House in Motion, the Magonista Autonomous Collective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elarsenal.net/2015/01/21/anarquistas-en-guerrero/|title=\"\u00bfAnarquistas en Guerrero?\" (In Spanish)|work=Arsenal Diario Digital|accessdate=2019-09-25}}</ref>, the Anarchist Student Coordinator, Cruz Negra Anarchist and the Frente Oriente Okupa Che.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/opinion/c%C3%A9lulas-anarquistas-al-acecho/ar-BBUqMmt|title=C\u00e9lulas anarquistas al acecho (In Spanish)|work=MSN Noticias|accessdate=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vanguardia.com.mx/5gruposanarquistasviolentosquetienenpresenciaeneledomex-1065907.html|title=5 grupos anarquistas violentos que tienen presencia en el Edomex (In Spanish)|work=Vanguardia|accessdate=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>https://www.univision.com/noticias/politica/un-grupo-anarquista-escribe-la-palabra-resistir-sobre-un-campo-de-golf-propiedad-de-trump</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n*[[Smuggling of firearms into Mexico]]\n*[[Mexican Drug War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Terrorism in Latin America}}\n{{Americas topic|Terrorism in}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/extreme-violence-and-terrorism-in-mexico Extreme Violence and Terrorism in Mexico]\n\n[[Category:Terrorism in Mexico| ]]\n[[Category:Organized crime events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Terrorism by country|Mexico]]\n[[Category:Crime in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrorism_in_Mexico"}
